COPY public.educational_contents (id, title, content_type, summary, full_content, author, publication_date, target_audience, keywords, document_path, is_published, created_at, updated_at, title_sw, summary_sw, full_content_sw) FROM stdin;
1	Family Flood Preparedness Guide	Guideline	Practical steps every household should take before, during and after floods.	Before the flood: know your evacuation route, prepare a go-bag with documents, water and a torch. During: move to higher ground immediately; never walk or drive through moving water. After: return only when authorities declare it safe; boil drinking water; report damage to your ward officer.	PMO-DMD	2026-05-29	Community	floods,preparedness,household	\N	t	2026-06-12 08:58:00.085632+00	2026-06-12 08:58:00.085632+00	\N	\N	\N
2	Understanding Early Warning Levels	Article	What Advisory, Warning and Major Warning mean — and what to do at each level.	Advisory (yellow): be aware and follow updates. Warning (orange): be prepared to act; secure property and review evacuation plans. Major Warning (red): take action now — follow instructions from local authorities without delay.	TMA	2026-05-13	Community,LGAs	early warning,alert levels	\N	t	2026-06-12 08:58:00.094902+00	2026-06-12 08:58:00.094902+00	\N	\N	\N
3	School Emergency Drill Handbook	Guideline	How schools plan and run evacuation drills each term.	Each school should map assembly points, assign teacher marshals, and run at least one full drill per term. This handbook provides the drill script, timing benchmarks and an after-action checklist.	PMO-DMD	2026-04-13	Schools	drills,schools,evacuation	\N	t	2026-06-12 08:58:00.099648+00	2026-06-12 08:58:00.099648+00	\N	\N	\N
5	Mpango wa Dharura wa Familia na Orodha ya Mkoba wa Dharura — Family Emergency Plan & Go-Bag Checklist	Guideline	Hatua rahisi za kuandaa mpango wa dharura wa familia na mkoba wa dharura. — Simple steps to build a family emergency plan and a ready go-bag.	Kila kaya inapaswa kuwa na mpango wa dharura. Kubaliana mahali pawili pa kukutana — moja karibu na nyumba na jingine nje ya mtaa — na namba ya mtu wa kuwasiliana naye nje ya eneo lenu. Andaa mkoba wa dharura wenye: maji (lita 3 kwa kila mtu kwa siku), chakula kisichoharibika, tochi na betri, redio ya betri, sanduku la huduma ya kwanza, dawa muhimu, nakala za nyaraka muhimu kwenye mfuko usiopitisha maji, filimbi, na pesa kidogo taslimu. Hakikisha kila mwanafamilia anajua jinsi ya kuzima umeme, gesi na maji. Fanya mazoezi ya mpango huu mara mbili kwa mwaka.\n\nEvery household should have an emergency plan. Agree two meeting points — one near the home and one outside the neighbourhood — and an out-of-area contact person. Build a go-bag with: water (3 litres per person per day), non-perishable food, a torch and batteries, a battery radio, a first-aid kit, essential medicines, copies of key documents in a waterproof bag, a whistle, and some cash. Make sure every family member knows how to switch off electricity, gas and water. Practise the plan twice a year.	PMO-DMD	2026-06-01	Households / Kaya	family plan, go-bag, preparedness, maandalizi, dharura	\N	t	2026-06-15 17:31:56.159623+00	2026-06-15 17:31:56.159623+00	\N	\N	\N
6	Usalama wa Tetemeko la Ardhi: Inama, Jifunike, Ng'ang'ania — Earthquake Safety: Drop, Cover and Hold On	Guideline	Hatua za kujikinga kabla, wakati na baada ya tetemeko la ardhi. — Protective actions before, during and after an earthquake.	Tetemeko la ardhi hutokea bila onyo. Hatua muhimu zaidi ni INAMA chini, JIFUNIKE chini ya meza imara, na NG'ANG'ANIA hadi mtetemeko ukome. Kabla: funga vitu vizito ukutani, tambua sehemu salama katika kila chumba, na andaa mkoba wa dharura. Wakati: kaa mbali na madirisha; ukiwa nje nenda eneo wazi; ukiwa kwenye gari simama kwa usalama. Baada: jiandae kwa mitetemeko ya kufuatia, kagua uvujaji wa gesi, na usiingie majengo yaliyoharibika.\n\nEarthquakes strike without warning. The most important action is to DROP, take COVER under sturdy furniture, and HOLD ON until the shaking stops. Before: secure heavy items to walls, identify a safe spot in each room, and prepare a go-bag. During: stay away from windows; if outside move to open ground; if driving pull over safely. After: expect aftershocks, check for gas leaks, and do not enter damaged buildings.	PMO-DMD	2026-05-20	General public / Umma	earthquake, tetemeko, drop cover hold, safety	\N	t	2026-06-15 17:31:56.16921+00	2026-06-15 17:31:56.16921+00	\N	\N	\N
7	Maandalizi ya Kimbunga kwa Jamii — Community Cyclone Preparedness	Guideline	Jinsi jamii za pwani zinavyojiandaa na kuhama wakati wa kimbunga. — How coastal communities prepare for and evacuate during a cyclone.	Fuatilia tahadhari za Mamlaka ya Hali ya Hewa Tanzania (TMA). Imarisha nyumba, tambua kituo cha hifadhi kilicho karibu, na kubaliana ishara za jamii za kuhama. Wakati wa kimbunga, baki ndani mbali na madirisha na usidanganywe na utulivu wa jicho la kimbunga. Baada, subiri tangazo rasmi, epuka maji yaliyofurika na nyaya za umeme zilizoanguka, na chemsha maji ya kunywa.\n\nFollow warnings from the Tanzania Meteorological Authority (TMA). Strengthen homes, identify the nearest evacuation centre, and agree community evacuation signals. During a cyclone, stay indoors away from windows and do not be fooled by the calm of the eye. Afterwards, wait for the official all-clear, avoid floodwater and fallen power lines, and boil drinking water.	TMA	2026-05-13	Coastal communities / Jamii za pwani	cyclone, kimbunga, TMA, evacuation, warning	\N	t	2026-06-15 17:31:56.17397+00	2026-06-15 17:31:56.17397+00	\N	\N	\N
8	Kuzuia Kipindupindu na Magonjwa ya Maji — Preventing Cholera and Waterborne Disease	Article	Usafi wa maji, mikono na mazingira ili kuzuia milipuko ya magonjwa. — Water, hand and environmental hygiene to prevent disease outbreaks.	Kipindupindu na magonjwa mengine ya maji huenea kupitia maji na chakula kilichochafuliwa. Kinga: nywa maji yaliyochemshwa au yaliyotibiwa, nawa mikono kwa sabuni mara kwa mara, tumia choo salama, na osha matunda na mboga kwa maji safi. Mtu akipata kuhara kwa wingi, mpe maji ya kuongeza maji mwilini (ORS) na mpeleke kituo cha afya haraka. Fuata taarifa rasmi za wizara ya afya wakati wa mlipuko.\n\nCholera and other waterborne diseases spread through contaminated water and food. Prevention: drink boiled or treated water, wash hands with soap regularly, use a safe latrine, and wash fruit and vegetables with clean water. If someone has heavy diarrhoea, give oral rehydration solution (ORS) and take them to a health centre quickly. Follow official health-ministry guidance during an outbreak.	Ministry of Health / WHO	2026-05-08	General public / Umma	cholera, kipindupindu, hygiene, ORS, waterborne	\N	t	2026-06-15 17:31:56.183837+00	2026-06-15 17:31:56.183837+00	\N	\N	\N
9	Usalama wa Moto Nyumbani — Fire Safety in the Home	Guideline	Kuzuia moto, kupanga njia ya kutoka, na nini cha kufanya moto ukitokea. — Preventing fire, planning an escape, and what to do if a fire starts.	Moto mwingi wa nyumbani unaepukika. Zima jiko na umeme usiouhitaji, usiache mishumaa au moto bila uangalizi, na weka kiberiti mbali na watoto. Panga njia mbili za kutoka kila chumba na mahali pa kukutania nje. Moto ukitokea: toka mara moja, tambaa chini ya moshi, na usirudi ndani. Ukiwaka, ACHA kutembea, LALA chini, na VIRINGISHA ili kuzima moto. Piga simu ya zimamoto mara tu ukiwa salama nje.\n\nMost home fires are preventable. Turn off stoves and unneeded electricity, never leave candles or open flame unattended, and keep matches away from children. Plan two escape routes from each room and an outdoor meeting point. If a fire starts: get out immediately, crawl low under smoke, and never go back inside. If your clothes catch fire, STOP, DROP and ROLL. Call the fire brigade once you are safely outside.	Fire & Rescue Force / Red Cross	2026-05-25	Households / Kaya	fire, moto, escape plan, stop drop roll, safety	\N	t	2026-06-15 17:31:56.1892+00	2026-06-15 17:31:56.1892+00	\N	\N	\N
10	Usalama wa Barabarani na Huduma ya Kwanza kwenye Ajali — Road Safety and First Response at Accidents	Article	Kuzuia ajali na hatua sahihi za kuokoa maisha unapokuta ajali. — Preventing crashes and the right life-saving steps when you reach an accident.	Ajali za barabarani ni chanzo kikubwa cha vifo. Kinga: funga mkanda wa usalama, vaa helmeti, usiendeshe ukiwa umelewa au umechoka, na fuata sheria za barabarani. Ukikuta ajali: hakikisha eneo ni salama, piga simu ya dharura, zuia damu kwa kitambaa safi, na usimsogeze mwenye jeraha la mgongo isipokuwa kuna hatari. Kama jeruhi hapumui na umefunzwa, anza CPR. Baki naye hadi wahudumu wafike.\n\nRoad crashes are a major cause of death. Prevention: wear a seatbelt, wear a helmet, never drive drunk or tired, and obey traffic laws. If you reach a crash: make sure the scene is safe, call emergency services, control bleeding with a clean cloth, and do not move someone with a back injury unless there is danger. If a casualty is not breathing and you are trained, start CPR. Stay with them until responders arrive.	WHO / Red Cross	2026-05-18	Drivers and general public / Madereva na umma	road safety, ajali, first aid, CPR, seatbelt	\N	t	2026-06-15 17:31:56.195649+00	2026-06-15 17:31:56.195649+00	\N	\N	\N
11	Afya Wakati wa Joto Kali — Heatwave Health: Staying Safe in Extreme Heat	Article	Kutambua na kuzuia magonjwa yatokanayo na joto kali. — Recognising and preventing heat-related illness.	Joto kali linaweza kusababisha upungufu wa maji mwilini, mkazo wa joto na kiharusi cha joto. Kunywa maji mara kwa mara, kaa kwenye kivuli, vaa nguo nyepesi, na epuka kazi nzito mchana. Waangalie zaidi wazee, watoto wadogo na wagonjwa wa muda mrefu. Dalili za hatari ni kizunguzungu, kichefuchefu, kuchanganyikiwa na kuacha kutoka jasho — mpoze mtu kwa maji na tafuta huduma ya afya haraka. Kamwe usimwache mtu au mnyama ndani ya gari lililofungwa.\n\nExtreme heat can cause dehydration, heat exhaustion and heat stroke. Drink water often, stay in the shade, wear light clothing, and avoid heavy work in the midday sun. Pay special attention to the elderly, young children and people with chronic illness. Danger signs are dizziness, nausea, confusion and stopping sweating — cool the person with water and seek medical care quickly. Never leave a person or pet inside a closed vehicle.	WHO / Ministry of Health	2026-05-30	General public / Umma	heat, joto, heat stroke, hydration, health	\N	t	2026-06-15 17:31:56.203166+00	2026-06-15 17:31:56.203166+00	\N	\N	\N
12	Maandalizi Jumuishi: Maafa na Watu Wenye Ulemavu — Inclusive Preparedness: Disasters and Persons with Disabilities	Guideline	Kuhakikisha watu wenye ulemavu hawaachwi nyuma katika maandalizi na uhamishaji. — Making sure persons with disabilities are not left behind in preparedness and evacuation.	Watu wenye ulemavu wako hatarini zaidi wakati wa maafa kama maandalizi hayawajumuishi. Panga mapema: tambua njia za kutoka zinazopitika, weka mtandao wa watu watakaosaidia, andaa mkoba wenye vifaa vya kusaidia na dawa za wiki kadhaa, na sajili mahitaji yako na kamati ya maafa ya mtaa/kijiji. Taarifa za tahadhari zitolewe katika miundo inayofikika — sauti, picha, maandishi na lugha ya alama. Familia na jamii zihakikishe kila mtu anajumuishwa katika mazoezi ya dharura.\n\nPersons with disabilities face greater risk in disasters when preparedness does not include them. Plan ahead: identify accessible exit routes, build a support network, prepare a bag with assistive devices and several weeks of medicines, and register your needs with the ward/village disaster committee. Warning information should be provided in accessible formats — audio, pictures, text and sign language. Families and communities should ensure everyone is included in emergency drills.	UNDRR / PMO-DMD	2026-06-05	Persons with disabilities and carers / Watu wenye ulemavu	inclusive, ulemavu, accessibility, disability, preparedness	\N	t	2026-06-15 17:31:56.208192+00	2026-06-15 17:31:56.208192+00	\N	\N	\N
13	Kuelewa Fahirisi ya Hatari ya INFORM — Understanding the INFORM Risk Index	Guide	How Tanzania measures disaster risk for every council with the INFORM methodology — Hazard & Exposure, Vulnerability and Lack of Coping Capacity, combined into a single 0–10 risk score.	INFORM is a global, open methodology for understanding the risk of humanitarian crises and disasters. INFORM Tanzania applies it at the subnational level — for all 195 councils (LGAs) — using the Tanzania Country Model.\n\nHOW RISK IS MEASURED\nINFORM Risk combines three dimensions, each scored from 0 (lowest) to 10 (highest):\n\n1. Hazard & Exposure — how often hazards occur and how many people and assets are exposed (drought, floods, earthquakes, storms, and more).\n2. Vulnerability — the conditions that make people more susceptible to harm (poverty, undernutrition, lack of access to services).\n3. Lack of Coping Capacity — the strength or weakness of institutions and infrastructure to prevent, prepare for and respond.\n\nThe three dimensions are combined with the INFORM formula:\n   Risk = cube root of (Hazard & Exposure × Vulnerability × Lack of Coping Capacity)\n\nEach council's score sits on a 0–10 scale and is grouped into five classes: Very Low, Low, Medium, High and Very High.\n\nHOW IT IS BUILT\nEvery dimension is built from indicators — official statistics standardised to a common 0–10 scale (min–max with outlier handling and, where needed, log transforms), averaged into components and categories, then combined using a scaled geometric mean. The result is one comparable risk score for each council, region and the nation.\n\nHOW TO USE IT\nINFORM Risk is structural and slow-changing. Use it to prioritise prevention, preparedness and resource allocation — to see where risk is concentrated and why. It is NOT an emergency alert system. For fast-evolving threats, INFORM Tanzania also publishes operational Earth-observation hazard signals as a separate, dynamic layer.\n\nExplore the live national risk map on this portal under "INFORM Risk".\n\n—\n\nINFORM ni mbinu ya kimataifa na huru ya kuelewa hatari ya majanga na maafa. INFORM Tanzania inaitumia katika ngazi ya halmashauri — kwa halmashauri zote 195 — kwa kutumia Modeli ya Nchi ya Tanzania. Hatari hupimwa kwa vipimo vitatu (Hatari na Athari, Uathirika, na Upungufu wa Uwezo wa Kukabiliana), kila kimoja katika kipimo cha 0–10, na kuunganishwa kuwa alama moja ya hatari. Tumia fahirisi hii kupanga kinga, maandalizi na ugawaji wa rasilimali — siyo mfumo wa tahadhari ya dharura.	Prime Minister's Office – Disaster Management Department	2026-06-26	Planners · DRM officers · Public	INFORM, risk index, hazard, exposure, vulnerability, coping capacity, methodology, subnational	\N	t	2026-06-26 16:35:17.19494+00	2026-06-26 16:35:17.19494+00	\N	\N	\N
